	stolen	from a Harvard Square music school, police have found the $24,
	000 instrument. But it's unclear if police ever plan to charge the
	crooks involved in the high-profile heist.
To: <msn-list@te.verweg.com>
Message-ID: <035e01c7b3be$20cf4080$626dc180$@org>
Content-Type: text/plain;	charset="us-ascii"

Weston Police help in search for violin

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
----
 Photo by Mark Thomson: http://www.townonline.com/weston/homepage/x398631723
Violinist Frederic Bednarz, a former student at the Longy School of Music,
had his antique violin worth $24,000 stolen from a locker in 2002. Police
recently recovered the instrument.By Erin Smith
GateHouse News Service
Tue Jun 19, 2007, 07:25 PM EDT 

----------------------------------------------------------------------------
----


Weston - Nearly five years after Frederic Bednarz's violin was stolen from a
Harvard Square music school, police have found the $24,000 instrument. But
it's unclear if police ever plan to charge the crooks involved in the
high-profile heist.
For Bednarz, a Montreal-born violinist, the return of the pricey
19th-century violin is a case of too little, too late.
"Well, you know, it's been such a long time that I've dealt with it and
bought another violin," said Bednarz.
In 2002, Bednarz's violin was stolen from his locker in the basement of the
Longy School of Music while he was at lunch. At the time, Bednarz had just
arrived in Boston for a two-year stint as a professional studies student at
school working toward his artist diploma in chamber music performance. Staff
and musicians searched the school for days, but couldn't find the violin,
which Bednarz had borrowed from his Montreal sponsor.
Then, last November, Weston Police received a tip about the violin and
Cambridge Police recovered the stolen instrument, according to Weston Police
Chief Steven Shaw. 
Investigators in Weston and Cambridge began working together on the case
when the violin was first stolen five years ago and revived the partnership
when Weston Police received the tip last year.
"It never really fell off the radar screen," said Shaw.
Police at both departments are keeping the details about the violin's
recovery under wraps. Cambridge Police are refusing to discuss the case or
say how the rare instrument was found. No one has been charged with the
theft, and it's unclear whether Cambridge Police ever plan to make an arrest
in the case. 
"That's all we're going to give out," said police spokesman Frank
Pasquarello, who refused to give a reason for withholding the information.
The violin was earlier rumored to be from the 1700s, one of the rare violins
still in existence today crafted by Italian Santo Serafin. More recently,
however, experts estimated the instrument was made in Venice, Italy, around
1800.
At the time of the theft, musicians suspected the violin was stolen by teens
who didn't know the value of the instrument. Police and instrument dealers
had said the rare violin would be hard to sell on the open market without
drawing attention.
The insurance company has since refunded the money for the instrument, and
Bednarz bought and tried playing several instruments in past years, finally
settling on another older instrument.
"It's not exactly what I had, but I like it," said Bednarz.
The insurance company sold Bednarz's stolen violin at Tarisio auction house
last month, according to Chris Reuning, owner of Reuning & Son Violins in
Boston.
The violin sold at auction for $24,150, said Reuning, one of the founding
partners of Tarisio.
Tarisio is the world's largest auction house for stringed instruments and
sells more than 2,000 violins, violas, cellos and bows each year.
As for Bednarz, he moved back to Montreal this week to play with the
Molinari Quartet and doesn't mind that his former violin has a new owner.
Said Bednarz, "That's OK. I'm sure someone's happy."

http://www.townonline.com/



