'No questions' if sculpture is returned

FOREST PARK, Ill., June 19 (UPI) -- The Forest Park, Ill., owners of a
missing 500-pound elephant sculpture say they won't press charges if the
item is returned. 
The 3-by-4 foot pachyderm is believed to have been taken last week from
outside an art studio and gallery, the Chicago Sun-Times reported Tuesday. 

"The owners say that if they get it back, there would be no questions
asked," Forest Park police Deputy Chief Tom Aftanas told the Sun-Times. 

The sculpture, which was decorated with thousands of brightly colored and
mirrored glass squares as part of the city's "Elephants on Parade" exhibit,
is believed to have been stolen Wednesday night or Thursday morning, the
newspaper said. 

"It would have taken some effort to move this thing," he said. "You could
see drag marks on the sidewalk." 

