Oslo police angered Interpol
The secretary-general of Interpol has criticized Norwegian police for
withholding information about the theft of the Munch paintings.
Police director Ingelin Killengreen rejected Interpol criticism.

The criticism has come in writing from Interpol secretary-general Ronald K.
Noble. In a two-page long letter he refers to repeated written and verbal
enquiries to Norwegian police about information about who was responsible
for the theft of the Munch masterpieces "The Scream" and "Madonna", without
receiving an answer.

"As a result of this, violent criminals who were responsible for one of the
major art thefts of recent decades are still not registered in Interpol's
database," Noble wrote according to newspaper VG.

Noble claims that the reticence of Norwegian police can have major
consequences, including an inability to hinder similar types of crimes in
the future.

Police Director Ingelin Killengreen rejected the criticism and told VG that
she had spoken with Noble two weeks ago.

"We said that we should have been better at informing them that we could not
supply this information. Due to considerations concerning the investigation
the Oslo police do not wish to supply the information Interpol has
requested," Killengreen said.

http://www.aftenposten.no/



